<h1 id="etch-beta2">Errata for etch beta 2</h1>

<p>
This is a list of known problems in the etch beta 2 release of the
Debian-Installer. If you do not see your problem listed here,
please send us an <a href="report-template">installation report</a>
describing the problem.
</p>

<dl class="gloss">
	<dt>Network and disk devices may change on reboot</dt>
	<dd>
	On systems with multiple disk or network controllers, the kernel/udev
	may assign a different device node on reboot of the system than was
	used during installation due to difference in load order of drivers.<br>
	This can lead to failure to boot the system or to the network not
	coming up automatically. In most cases this can be rectified changing
	the bootloader configuration and /etc/fstab, or /etc/network/interfaces,
	possibly using the rescue mode of the installer.<br>
	Note however that this problem may occur again on subsequent boots.
	Fixing this issue has priority for the next release of Debian installer.
	</dd>

	<dt>Use of network mirrors during CD/DVD installs</dt>
	<dd>
	By default a network mirror will be added to your sources list, even when
	you install from a full CD or DVD. This means that, after task selection,
	packages for which a newer version is available on the mirror will be
	downloaded over the network instead of being read from CD/DVD.<br>
	It is possible to work around this by using the &lt;Go back&gt; button when
	you are asked to select a mirror and skipping to the next installation
	step when you get to the menu. When you are asked once more if you want
	to use a mirror later in the installation, select the option "Ignore".<br>
	Note: the security mirror may still be used.<br>
	</dd>

	<dt>Issues during package installation for some languages</dt>
	<dd>
	Languages that have not been set to use UTF-8 by default will see
	garbled text during package installation because of character encoding
	problems (mojibake). This is a known issue for installations in Russian.
	</dd>

	<dt>General issues after reboot because of UTF-8 default</dt>
	<dd>
	The installed system is now set to UTF-8 by default. However, not all
	applications properly support UTF-8 yet, which may result in minor or
	major problems when using them.
	<dd>
	Please check if such problems have been reported yet and, if not, file
	a bug report against the relevant package (not the installer).
	</dd>

	<dt>Non i386 installs: mirror list may not be correct</dt>
	<dd>
	Debian is currently undergoing a restructuring of its archive mirrors.
	In practice this means that archives which previously supported all
	(or most) architectures may no longer do so. The installer includes a
	static list of which mirrors support which architectures and, because
	of this change, this list may be outdated.<br>The mirror selection
	component in the installer <strong>does not</strong> check if an architecture is
	actually available on a mirror, but only if the mirror supports the
	release being installed. If a mirror has dropped the architecture,
	this may result in errors during download of d-i components or during
	package installation.<br> The solution of course is to find a mirror
	that does support your architecture and to use that. This issue only
	affects architectures other than i386.
	</dd>

	<dt>Limited localization of installed system</dt>
	<dd>
	For the Sarge version of the installer the package localization-config was
	responsible for part of the localization of the installed system. This
	package ran as part of base-config, which has been dropped in the release.
	Adapting localization-config to run before the reboot is on our TODO list,
	but meanwhile some localization may not be done automatically when
	installing in languages other than English.
	</dd>

	<dt>Installation of Sarge not supported</dt>
	<dd>
	As a result of some structural changes in this release of the installer,
	installation of Sarge (stable) is not supported. We expect to make this
	possible again in the next release.
	</dd>

	<dt>CD-ROM drives connected to SATA controllers not detected</dt>
	<dd>
	Cause for the drives not being detected is that libata ATAPI support
	is not enabled in the kernel as the upstream kernel developers do not
	yet consider it mature. It is expected to be enabled in 2.6.16 kernels.<br>
	A <a href="http://wiki.debian.org/DebianInstaller/SataAtapiHowto">\
	workaround is available</a> that will allow users to enable ATAPI
	support manually for the installation and the installed system.
	</dd>

	<dt>Several issues for PowerPC</dt>
	<dd>
	The PowerPC port has several issues in this release:
	<ul>
		<li>support for prep partitions in partman is broken</li>
		<li>tg3 driver not available during installation</li>
		<li>floppy installations for powerpc are broken because no
		    device node is created for the swim3 module</li>
	        <li>Oldworld powerpc boot floppies will not work as miboot
		    is not included</li>
	</ul>
	</dd>

	<dt>amd64: packages may be missing from CD images</dt>
	<dd>
	At the time of the release, the AMD64 etch archive was known to be
	missing some packages due to a reversed migration from unstable. This
	has resulted in KDE not being included on full CD images for AMD64
	(because of missing libcupsys2). Other packages may be affected as well.
	</dd>

	<dt>arm: CATS cdrom images missing essential drivers</dt>
	<dd>
	Please use netboot or daily (sid_d-i) images instead.
	</dd>

	<dt>i386: netinst iso too large for USB stick installs</dt>
	<dd>
	The netinst iso is too large to fit on a 128 mb USB stick. It will
	work as a regular CD image or on larger USB sticks for a USB
	install.
	</dd>

